1) Voting on their own salary increases

Legislators are considering an amendment to increase pensions of a select few lawmakers/employees, while others in the system haven't gotten so much as a cost of living adj. in a decade. @MattFriedmanNJ explains: https://t.co/PseMEVTxG4

Why does this happen? Because if bills like this were debated more publicly - the party in power would find out that they need some tweaking, are not all that popular, or all together shouldn‚Äôt be passed.

A bit more on the votes happening today...
Today is the last day of New Jersey‚Äôs legislative session - so that means everything from lawmaker pay increases, to controversial bills on life, and gun control are being forced through.

This is an issue that should be easy for Congress to come together on - especially considering we have over 70 veterans serving in the House. Looking forward to working alongside members like @JakeEllzey @RepGallagher @DanCrenshawTX @RepLeeZeldin @RepMeijer

Our men and women in uniform chose to serve our country for something much greater than a paycheck, but we have to do better. This is a problem government can fix. The President and Congress have the power to ignore the ECI and propose lower or higher increases.

This is not only an urgent national defense issue - Feeding America reports that nearly 160,000 military members are struggling to feed their families. This is because some newly enlisted members are only taking home around 17k after tax - hovering near the US poverty line

All this at a time when millions of Americans are leaving their jobs to chase higher wages. With the rising threats posed by China, Russia and continued instability in the Middle East, we cannot afford low morale or high troop turnover.

Not only are military wages effectively decreasing, 48,000 service members will lose their Continental United States Cost-of-Living Allowance (CONUS COLA) benefit. These modest monthly payments are given to troops stationed in high-cost areas.

This is because troop raises are not currently tied to CPI but rather based on ECI (Employment Cost Index) from the year before, resulting in military wages increases being tied to data that is two years old when the increases take effect.

This year US service members will effectively receive a pay and benefits cut.

The 2022 defense budget increased by 5%, but troop salaries will receive little benefit from the increased spending. Salaries will improve by just 2.7% while inflation is more than 2.5x that. https://t.co/7jmwNYsPwv
